\section PydanticSpecOverview Overview

The Pydantic models in \c dakota/python/dakota/spec constitute the canonical
specification of Dakota's input grammar. Implement grammar edits and
additions in these Python models and, where required, provide matching
C++ validation or computed-field implementations so that the shared
grammar contract remains consistent between schema generation and runtime.

Most models inherit from \c DakotaBaseModel
(\c dakota/python/dakota/spec/base.py). Parsed fields are declared with
\c DakotaField and represent user-visible keywords and arguments.
\c ValidationRule subclasses capture checks or mutations that depend on
multiple parsed fields. \c ComputedFieldSpec entries paired with
\c @computed_field properties export derived values in the schema
or validated models. This page is self-contained: procedural steps reference
the detailed authoring sections that follow; readers may consult any
section on demand.

\section PydanticSpecProcedure Procedure: Adding a New Keyword

Follow these steps when adding a new keyword. Each step references the
authoritative section on this page that documents the required authoring
surface and implementation details.

<ol>
<li>Decide grammar role and one-of semantics.
Choose whether the keyword is a scalar or collection argument, a pointer-
style keyword that names another block, a Union branch, or a selection-
wrapper (method or model family). If the keyword participates in a \c Union,
ensure the Python annotation, \c default/\c default_factory, and
\c dakota \c union_pattern metadata express identical one-of semantics.
See \ref PydanticSpecUnions.</li>

<li>Declare the parsed field on the appropriate model class.
Add a typed class attribute to a \c DakotaBaseModel-derived class and
declare it with \c DakotaField. Provide Pydantic parameters
(\c default, \c default_factory, \c description, bounds) as appropriate.
Include \c dakota metadata keys only as required: \c aliases,
\c argument, \c block_pointer, \c anchor, \c union_pattern,
\c model_default, \c internal_only, and \c materialization. For a new
method or model selection, follow the selection-wrapper pattern described
in \ref PydanticSpecDakotaField and \ref PydanticSpecAddModel.</li>

<li>Author materialization mapping to IR.
Select the IR key or keys that the field should modify and author the
materialization metadata describing the write instructions. Each item
must include at minimum \c ir_key, \c storage_type, and
\c ir_value_type. Some \c storage_type values require additional
properties (\c stored_value, \c secondary_ir_key,
\c secondary_ir_value_type, \c enum_scope,
\c secondary_literal_value). Prefer reusing existing storage-type handlers
for identical IR effects; for domain-specific shapes use an existing
model as a template. See \ref PydanticSpecMaterialization.</li>

<li>Select the IR-default source.
Choose one canonical source for any IR key's default: a grammar-level
default on the Pydantic field, an implementation-level override in
\c default_overrides_registry.json, or a type-policy default in
\c default_policy_registry.json. The IR codegen merges these disjoint
sources; \c generate_ir_tables.py treats collisions as errors. See
\ref PydanticSpecIrDefaults.</li>

<li>Add validation rules or computed fields if required.
If correctness depends on relationships among fields, author a
\c ValidationRule subclass, attach it via \c _VALIDATION_RULES on the
model, and provide the matching C++ implementation and registration. If a
derived value must appear in schema or the validated model, add a
\c ComputedFieldSpec to \c _COMPUTED_FIELDS and implement the
corresponding \c @computed_field property with a matching C++
registration. Both features require exact string-name agreement between
Python metadata and the C++ registry entries. See
\ref PydanticSpecValidation.</li>

<li>Implement and register required C++ logic and bindings.
Any new \c ValidationRule or computed-field function requires a C++
declaration and implementation, registration in the appropriate registry
constructor, and exposure via pybind so the Python layer can invoke it.
Typical files to edit are under
\c packages/dakota_parser/dakota_validation (include, src, and test).
Ensure the registered C++ string names match the Python metadata. See
\ref PydanticSpecValidation.</li>

<li>Regenerate schema and run IR code generation.
Generate JSON schema from the updated Pydantic models and confirm that
\c x-materialization, \c x-model-validations, \c x-computed-fields, and
\c x-model-default metadata appear as expected. Run
\c dakota/src/ir_codegen/extract_defaults_from_schema.py and
\c dakota/src/ir_codegen/generate_ir_tables.py and inspect the generated
IR contracts and write-instruction tables. Confirm intended \c ir_keys,
\c ir_value_types, and defaults are present and that no collisions exist.
See \ref PydanticSpecMaterialization and \ref PydanticSpecIrDefaults.</li>

<li>Test, document, and publish.
Add or update Python unit tests for parsing and schema output and C++
tests for validation and computed-field behavior. Execute integration
tests that exercise materialization through \c ProblemDescDB reads.
Update documentation and example inputs to demonstrate the new keyword.
Verify CI and style checks succeed before submitting the change.</li>
</ol>

\section PydanticSpecUnions How Union fields are processed

Dakota recognizes several \c Union patterns to express one-of semantics.
The \c DakotaBaseModel layer applies a model-level validator to enforce
single-branch selection for \c Union fields represented as single-field
wrapper models. The wrapper field name is the user-visible discriminator.

Example:
\code
trend: Union[TrendNone, ExperimentalGPTrendConstant, ExperimentalGPTrendLinear]
\endcode

Accepted user input is a single-key dictionary matching a branch wrapper,
for example \c {"linear": {...}} or \c {"none": true}.

\subsection PydanticSpecUnionPattern1 Pattern 1: Optional with model default

Python shape: \c Union[OptionA,...] with a model \c default_factory.

Semantics: omission yields a meaningful default branch.

\subsection PydanticSpecUnionPattern2 Pattern 2: Optional with no default branch

Python shape: \c Union[OptionA,...] | None with \c default=None.

Semantics: omission disables the feature.

\subsection PydanticSpecUnionPattern3 Pattern 3: Three-state optional with default branch

Python shape: \c Union[OptionA,...,dict] | None with
\c default_factory.

Semantics: omission => disabled; \c {} => enabled with defaults; branch
object => enabled with explicit configuration.

\subsection PydanticSpecUnionPattern4 Pattern 4: Required Union

Python shape: \c Union[OptionA,...].

Semantics: user must select a branch.

\subsection PydanticSpecUnionPattern5 Pattern 5: Three-state optional without grammar default

Python shape: \c Union[OptionA,...,dict] | None with \c default=None.

Semantics: omission => disabled; \c {} => implementation defaults; branch
=> explicit.

\subsection PydanticSpecUnionPattern6 Pattern 6: Required parent with optional subselection

Python shape: \c Union[OptionA,...,dict].

Semantics: parent must exist; \c {} is a valid "no subselection" choice.

\subsection PydanticSpecUnionRuntime Runtime validation rules

<ul>
<li>If a \c Union has multiple branches, exactly one branch must be
    selected.</li>
<li>Validated model instances matching a branch are accepted.</li>
<li>Dictionaries with more than one key fail validation.</li>
<li>Unrecognized keys fail validation.</li>
<li>If \c dict is a branch, empty-dictionary semantics depend on the
    pattern.</li>
<li>For Pattern 3, omission converts to \c None while \c {} instantiates
    from \c default_factory, preserving three states.</li>
</ul>

\subsection PydanticSpecUnionAuthoring Authoring guidance

<ul>
<li>Record the intended pattern with \c union_pattern.</li>
<li>Set \c model_default when the pattern specifies a default branch.</li>
<li>Keep the Python annotation, \c default/\c default_factory,
    \c union_pattern, and \c model_default consistent.</li>
</ul>

\section PydanticSpecDakotaField DakotaField authoring

\c DakotaField extends \c pydantic.Field with a \c dakota dictionary that
controls parser, schema, and materialization behavior. Standard Pydantic
kwargs (\c default, \c default_factory, \c description, \c gt, \c ge,
etc.) remain valid.

Common \c dakota keys:
<ul>
<li>\c aliases: \c list[str] or \c str for accepted alternative
    spellings.</li>
<li>\c block_pointer: string naming the referenced block family/role.</li>
<li>\c argument: child field treated as inline parameter.</li>
<li>\c anchor: boolean \c True to attach branches to parent context.</li>
<li>\c union_pattern: integer pattern id for one-of semantics.</li>
<li>\c model_default: default branch name for patterns with defaults.</li>
<li>\c internal_only: boolean to reject user input for the field.</li>
<li>\c materialization: \c list[dict] describing IR writes and presence
    effects.</li>
</ul>

Notes:
<ul>
<li>Use \c aliases only for backward compatibility.</li>
<li>Use \c block_pointer when the keyword names another block.</li>
<li>Use \c argument when a child field acts as the inline argument.</li>
<li>Use \c anchor=True only when grammar requires attached
    discriminators.</li>
<li>\c internal_only fields are rejected from user input by
    \c DakotaBaseModel.</li>
</ul>

Example:
\code
directory_tag: Literal[True] | None = DakotaField(
    default=None,
    description="Tag evaluation directories with identifiers",
    dakota={"aliases": ["dir_tag"]},
)
\endcode

\section PydanticSpecMaterialization Materialization and IR writes

Materialization maps validated Pydantic JSON into Dakota's IR. The models
describe valid input, \c dakota["materialization"] prescribes how input affects
IR keys, and the IR codegen emits write-instruction tables.

Pipeline:
- Models export JSON schema with \c x-materialization metadata.
- Codegen scripts under \c dakota/src/ir_codegen read schema and produce IR
  contracts and write tables.
- At runtime, validated JSON is traversed and generated write instructions
  populate IR keys consumed by \c ProblemDescDB.

Key scripts:
- \c dakota/src/ir_codegen/extract_defaults_from_schema.py
- \c dakota/src/ir_codegen/generate_ir_tables.py

Materialization item shape:
- \c ir_key: destination IR key.
- \c storage_type: write-handler identifier.
- \c ir_value_type: Dakota IR type (\c Real, \c size_t,
  \c StringArray, \c short, etc.).
- \c stored_value: optional literal for presence-driven writes.
- Additional handler-specific properties as required.

Common materialization cases:
These are the \c storage_type values authors are most likely to use when
adding or editing grammar.

\htmlonly
<table border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="4">
<thead>
<tr>
  <th><code>storage_type</code></th>
  <th>expected fields</th>
  <th>when to use</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
  <td><code>DIRECT_VALUE</code></td>
  <td><code>ir_key</code>, <code>ir_value_type</code></td>
  <td>Write the field's validated value directly to the IR key. Use for
  1:1 scalar or collection values.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td><code>ADD_TO_VALUE</code></td>
  <td><code>ir_key</code>, <code>ir_value_type</code></td>
  <td>Add the field's value into an existing numeric aggregate instead of
  replacing it. Use for roll-up counters.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td><code>PRESENCE_TRUE</code></td>
  <td><code>ir_key</code>, <code>ir_value_type</code></td>
  <td>Set the target IR key to boolean true when the field is present.
  Use for presence-driven boolean flags.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td><code>PRESENCE_FALSE</code></td>
  <td><code>ir_key</code>, <code>ir_value_type</code></td>
  <td>Set the target IR key to boolean false when the field is present.
  Use for presence-driven negating flags.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td><code>PRESENCE_LITERAL</code></td>
  <td><code>ir_key</code>, <code>ir_value_type</code>, <code>stored_value</code>[, <code>enum_scope</code>]</td>
  <td>Write a literal <code>stored_value</code> when the field is present. Use when
  presence selects a specific enumerated or literal runtime value.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td><code>PRESENCE_ENUM</code></td>
  <td><code>ir_key</code>, <code>ir_value_type</code>, <code>stored_value</code>[, <code>enum_scope</code>]</td>
  <td>Presence selects one of a set of enumerated IR values. Use when the
  field is a symbolic enumerant.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td><code>AUGMENT_ENUM</code></td>
  <td><code>ir_key</code>, <code>ir_value_type</code>, <code>stored_value</code></td>
  <td>Augment an enum-like IR setting with an additional symbolic value.
  Use when presence should extend an enumerated configuration.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td><code>TYPE_DATA_COMBINED</code></td>
  <td><code>ir_key</code>, <code>ir_value_type</code>, <code>stored_value</code>, <code>secondary_ir_key</code>, <code>secondary_ir_value_type</code></td>
  <td>Composite handler: primary literal selection plus secondary direct
  value write. Use when a symbolic choice and an argument are required.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td><code>METHOD_PIECEWISE</code></td>
  <td><code>ir_key</code>, <code>ir_value_type</code>, <code>stored_value</code>, <code>secondary_ir_key</code>, <code>secondary_ir_value_type</code>, <code>secondary_literal_value</code></td>
<td>Composite handler for piecewise method semantics; expands into
  primitive writes during codegen. Use for piecewise method configs.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
\endhtmlonly

