\section PydanticSpecIrDefaults IR default values

IR defaults ensure a complete runtime IR even when users omit inputs.
The generator merges three disjoint sources:

- schema-extracted defaults recorded in
  \c dakota/src/schema_defaults_extracted.json;
- explicit override defaults in
  \c dakota/src/default_overrides_registry.json;
  and
- type-policy defaults in
  \c dakota/src/default_policy_registry.json.

The generator reads these via \c load_schema_defaults(),
\c load_overrides(), and \c load_policies() and merges them into per-block
IR contracts. Place
a default in the Pydantic model when it is a grammar-level default.
Use \c default_overrides_registry.json when the default is implementation-
specific or not representable in schema. Use the policy registry for
ordinary type zero/false/empty defaults. Ensure only one source claims
an IR key; collisions cause \c generate_ir_tables.py to error.

\section PydanticSpecAddModel Adding a new method or model

Follow the selection-wrapper pattern when adding a method or model family.

Steps:
- Create a module in \c dakota/python/dakota/spec/method or
  \c dakota/python/dakota/spec/model.
- Define a config class for the body; reuse mixins for shared syntax.
- Declare parsed keywords as typed class attributes with \c DakotaField.
- Define a single-field selection wrapper inheriting from
  \c MethodSelection or \c ModelSelection. The wrapper must contain
  exactly one field named with
  the user-visible keyword.
- Import the wrapper in package \c __init__.py so it becomes part of the
  union assembly (\c MethodUnion or \c ModelUnion).

Minimal example:
\code
class MyMethodConfig(DakotaBaseModel):
    max_iterations: int | None = DakotaField(default=None, description="...")

class MyMethodSelection(MethodSelection):
    my_method: MyMethodConfig = DakotaField(...)
\endcode

\section PydanticSpecValidation Validation rules and computed fields

Validation rules and computed fields constitute part of the shared grammar
contract and require coordinated Python and C++ changes. The Python side
provides schema metadata and dispatch; the authoritative execution logic
resides in the C++ \c dakota_validation module.

To add a \c ValidationRule:
- Implement a \c ValidationRule subclass in
  \c dakota/python/dakota/spec/validation.
- Call \c super().__init__ with rule name, context, referenced fields, literals,
  and error message.
- Implement \c __call__(self,\ instance) to dispatch to C++ via
  \c _call_cpp_validator.
- Add C++ declaration and implementation in
  \c packages/dakota_parser/dakota_validation.
- Register the rule name in \c ValidatorRegistry::ValidatorRegistry().
- Expose the function via pybind in \c bindings.cpp.
- Add/update C++ tests under
  \c packages/dakota_parser/dakota_validation/test.
- Attach the rule on the model via \c _VALIDATION_RULES.

Validation call contract:
- \c instance: model serialized to \c dict.
- \c fields: paths from \c validationFields.
- \c literals: from \c validationLiterals.
- \c context: descriptive string.
- return: \c dict of mutations or empty \c dict for check-only rules.

To add a computed field:
- Declare \c _COMPUTED_FIELDS:\ ClassVar[dict[str,\ ComputedFieldSpec]]
  on the model.
- Add a matching \c @computed_field property that computes the value.
- Implement C++ declaration and function in \c computed_fields.hpp and source.
- Register the function in
  \c ComputedFieldRegistry::ComputedFieldRegistry().
- Ensure pybind bindings expose the function.
- Add/update C++ tests.

Example:
\code
_COMPUTED_FIELDS: ClassVar[dict[str, ComputedFieldSpec]] = {
    "lower_bounds": ComputedFieldSpec(
        function="discrete_set_str_lower_bounds",
        description="Lower bounds: min element per variable",
        return_type=list[str],
    ),
}

@computed_field
@property
def lower_bounds(self) -> List[str]:
    return DiscreteSetStrBounds.lower_bounds(self)
\endcode

\c DakotaBaseModel.__init_subclass__ detects \c _VALIDATION_RULES and
\c _COMPUTED_FIELDS and exports them as \c x-model-validations and
\c x-computed-fields in schema. Keep Python property names,
\c ComputedFieldSpec function strings, and C++ registry entries in exact
agreement.

\section PydanticSpecFloat DakotaFloat

Use DakotaFloat for fields that may carry non-finite values (NaN, inf,
-inf). DakotaFloat is an Annotated float with a custom serializer:
- finite values remain numeric;
- NaN serializes as "nan";
- +inf serializes as "inf";
- -inf serializes as "-inf".

This preserves compatibility between Python JSON and downstream C++
handling. Prefer DakotaFloat for fields that historically used sentinel
floating values (e.g., DBL_MAX or -DBL_MAX).

*/

} // namespace Dakota
